Preheat your oven to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9.

Bring a large saucepan of water to the boil with @salt{1/4%tsp} for the pasta.

Halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Cut into 2cm chunks and pop onto a #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until softened, ~{15-18%minutes}.

While the pepper chunks roast, add the @linguine{180%g} to your #pot{} of boiling water and bring back to the boil. Cook until tender, ~{12%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} and pop back in the pot. Drizzle with @oil{} and stir through to stop it sticking together.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium heat.

Once the oil is hot, add the @British chicken breast{260%g}(diced), @diced chorizo{60%g} and @mushrooms{120%g}(sliced). Fry until golden, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Add the garlic and stir-fry for ~{30%seconds}, then stir in the @finely chopped tomatoes{1/2%carton}, @vegetable stock paste{10%g}, @sun-dried tomato paste{25%g}, @sugar{1/2%tsp} and @water{50%ml} for the sauce.

Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Bring to the boil and simmer until thickened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging. It's cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Once the sauce has thickened, combine the roasted pepper, cooked pasta and sauce in whichever pot is the largest.

Stir in half the @hard Italian style cheese{20%g}(grated), adding a splash of @water{} if it's a little too thick.

Season to taste with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed.

Share your mushroom and chorizo linguine between your bowls.

Sprinkle with the remaining cheese to finish.

Enjoy!